 evictions and gentrification, and the networked labour of displaced populations that underpins growing urban economies. Central throughout is a critical analysis of how the discursive figure of the ‘internally displaced person’ is co-produced by various actors. The book argues that this label exerts significant power in structuring socio-economic inequalities and the politics of group belonging within different Somali cities connected through protracted histories of conflict-related migration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCities and townsxGrowthzSomalia. 0aForced migrationxSocial aspectszSomalia. 0aInternal migrantsxSocial conditionszSomalia. 0aMigration, InternalxClimatic factorszSomalia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / African.2bisacsh1 aChonka, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z97831111967940 cprintz978152921523640uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781529215250?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529215250423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529215250/original  a978-3-11-119679-4  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles